e disciplinary and institutional, political and economic range covering specific restrictions linked to speech codes, the interests of donors, institutional review board licensing, political pressure groups, and government policy, as well as phenomena of high generality, such as intellectual orthodoxy, in which coercion is barely visible and often self-imposed.As the editors say in their introduction: "No freedom can be taken for granted, even in the most well-functioning of formal democracies. Exposing the tendencies that undermine freedom of inquiry and their hidden sources and widespread implications is in itself an exercise in and for democracy."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAcademic freedomxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aAcademic freedomzUnited States. 0aTeaching, Freedom ofzUnited States. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Social.2bisacsh1 aBilgrami, Akeel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilgrami, Akeel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBromwich, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChomsky, Noam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Jonathan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCole, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElster, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFish, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamburger, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular